        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="TNYAdobeCaslonPro, 'Times New Roman', serif;" color="#000000" >

          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:400; margin-top:2px;">Why does China have cable cutters?</h2>
        </mj-text>
        
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px; line-height:1.5;">
          A few weeks ago, it was reported that China had developed a compact <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-3-may-25-tbq-h1-4-deep-sea-cable-cutting-device" target="_blank">deep-sea cable-cutting device</a> capable of severing communication lines. It can cut fortified cables at depths of 4,000 meters and was described as a development that could reset the global structure. However, reports indicate that China's undersea cable cutter is <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-3-may-25-tbq-h1-5-more-of-a-political-theatre" target="_blank">more of a political theatre</a> than a breakthrough.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px; line-height:1.5;">
          Experts say the technology isn’t very advanced. Many ships already have tools to sever cables. They say that below 1,500 metres, cables aren't armoured, negating the need for a super-powered cutter. However, the cutter fits into China's “grey zone” tactics to pressure Taiwan and deter Western powers. </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px; line-height:1.5;">
          The cutter helps China present a narrative that the West is failing in its infrastructure. China showcases itself as an alternative with its high-tech cable-laying vessels and capacity to keep infrastructure safe. </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px; line-height:1.5;">
          Analysts warn that long-term threats, such as seabed mining, carry greater risks to undersea cable networks, especially near the Pacific Islands. With no clear accountability, these mining operations could accidentally damage infrastructure or hide sabotage.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px; line-height:1.5;">
          While the cutter garners more attention, China’s increasing control over undersea infrastructure through construction, repair, and gateway to remote seabeds is likely to have a larger role in reshaping global communications and geopolitics.</p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
